ue: {y_test[idx]:15s} | Predicted: {y_pred_final[idx]:15s}\")"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"44b77812","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.021771,"end_time":"2026-03-20T01:38:29.619886","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-03-20T01:38:29.598115","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["## 5. Summation and Final Thoughts\n","\n","We implemented the Principal Component Analysis algorithm manually, calculating the eigenvalues to reduce the dimensionality.\n","\n","And then we implemented the K-Nearest Neighbor Classifier manually, iterating through the different k values to find the optimal value. \n","\n","We visuallized the data computed along the way to see if our implementation is satisfactory. \n","\n","### 5.1. Further Improvements\n","\n","We used PCA to reduce the dimensionality from 16 to 2, which is about 80% reduction, which leads to somewhat skewed data. And increasing the dimensionality to 4 would make things more accurate. Also, considering the size of the data, and the computational cost of calculating the k value over 15 would be expensive, but increasing the k value somewhat more would lead to increasing the accuracy as well.\n","\n","### 5.2. Citations\n","\n","    GeeksforGeeks. “Principal Component Analysis (PCA).” GeeksforGeeks, November 13, 2025. https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/data-analysis/principal-component-analysis-pca/.\n","\n","    GeeksforGeeks. “How to Find the Optimal Value of K in KNN.” GeeksforGeeks, July 23, 2025. https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/how-to-find-the-optimal-value-of-k-in-knn/."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"id":"9c156364","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.020413,"end_time":"2026-03-20T01:38:29.660909","exception":false,"start_time":"2026-03-20T01:38:29.640496","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"outputs":[],"source":[]}],"metadata":{"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"databundleVersionId":3450473,"datasetId":2048855,"sourceId":3398802,"sourceType":"datasetVersion"}],"docker